videos.headline: Wichita State blows it open with back-to-back dunks
videos.description: Shaquille Morris throws down an explosive dunk and Rashard Kelly goes coast-to-coast for another in the first 30 seconds against Oklahoma.

videos.headline: Young knocking in 3's for Oklahoma
videos.description: Trae Young drains a couple of nice 3-pointers in the first half and leads Oklahoma with 16 points so far in the game against Wichita State.

videos.headline: Oklahoma's McNeace rises up for vicious block
videos.description: Jamuni McNeace denies Samajae Hayes-Jones at the basket and Brady Manek gets it down the court for an easy layup in the first half against Wichita State.

videos.headline: Morris can't stop Young's ridiculous 3-pointer
videos.description: Trae Young gets past Shaquille Morris and drains a beautiful triple to extend the Sooners' lead to 43-32 in the first half against Wichita State.

videos.headline: Young playing like the pros against Wichita State
videos.description: Rich Hollenberg and Tom Crean compare Trae Young's game to superstars like Steph Curry and Damian Lillard after Young scored 21 points in the first half against Wichita State.

videos.headline: Frankamp finds Willis for back-to-back buckets
videos.description: Conner Frankamp makes a couple of nice assists to Darral Willis Jr. for a slam dunk and a triple in the second half against Oklahoma.

videos.headline: McNeace rejects Jones again
videos.description: Jamuni McNeace elevates for another monster block on Samajae Hayes-Jones in the second half.

videos.headline: Shockers' Brown leads Morris for the dunk
videos.description: Zach Brown throws a nice pass to Shaquille Morris for the flush in the second half.

videos.headline: Morris puts pressure on Sooners
videos.description: Shaquille Morris rises up for a big block with less than seven minutes to go in the game against Oklahoma.

videos.headline: Reaves' big 3-pointer for Shockers
videos.description: Austin Reaves gets the rebound and drains a triple to make it a 10-point game in the second half against the Sooners.

videos.headline: Frankamp's triple gives Shockers a chance
videos.description: Shaquille Morris finds Conner Frankamp who knocks in a 3-pointer from the right wing with less than 30 seconds left in the game.

videos.headline: Oklahoma's Young: My main focus is winning
videos.description: Trae Young breaks down his 29-point performance in Oklahoma's victory over Wichita State.

videos.headline: Trae Young reminiscent of Steph
videos.description: Trae Young looked awfully similar to the Steph Curry we saw at Davidson during Saturday's win.

video.title: Young gives Steph Curry-like performance

article.headline: Oklahoma takes down No. 3 Wichita State 91-83

images.name: Young gives Steph Curry-like performance
images.caption: Trae Young puts up 29 points in style while the Sooners upset Wichita State.

article.linkText: Oklahoma takes down No. 3 Wichita State 91-83
article.story:
WICHITA, Kan. -- No one had to convince Oklahoma's players that Saturday's game at No. 3 Wichita State presented a measuring stick of sorts.

Sooners star guard Trae Young believes the 91-83 victory "will open a lot of eyes in the college basketball world," and fellow freshman Brady Manek agreed.

"That's probably the biggest crowd I've ever played in front of," Manek said. "We just showed that we can play on a big stage against a great team."

Young, the nation's leading scorer, led the way. He finished with 29 points and 10 assists, but it was his 16 points on 6-of-9 shooting in the game's first 9 minutes that set the tone for the Sooners (8-1).

Young has scored at least 28 points in seven straight games.

Manek scored 16 of his 21 points in the first half for Oklahoma. Christian James and Kamron McGusty each had 13 points for the Sooners.

Darral Willis came off the bench to lead the Shockers (8-2) with 20 points and 12 rebounds. Landry Shamet had 17 points, Conner Frankamp scored 14 and Shaquille Morris added 10 for Wichita.

"We let them get comfortable in the first half," Wichita State coach Gregg Marshall said, "and you can't do that against a team that talented and that well-coached."

Behind Young and Manek, Oklahoma stormed to a 54-39 halftime lead. The Shockers entered Saturday allowing 68.2 points a game. The Sooners were 20 of 40 from the field and 10 of 23 from the 3-point line in the half.

"That's probably our best half because Wichita State is really good," Sooners coach Lon Kruger said.

Wichita State trailed 80-63 with 7:15 remaining but held Oklahoma scoreless for nearly 6 minutes. The Shockers closed within 84-78 but got no closer.

Marshall marveled at Young.

"I haven't coached against a freshman that plays the game at that level," Marshall said. "Hedging, switching; we tried everything against him. Trae Young is not going to get rattled. He is too good."

REBOUNDING

Wichita State entered the game leading the nation with a rebounding margin of 14.6 per game. The Sooners and Shockers each finished with 43 rebounds.

"Rebounding was a five-man effort," Kruger said. "Our guys knew how great they are at it. We talked about it all week."

DOWNTOWN DOWNTURN

Wichita State played its eighth game at Intrust Bank Arena, which will host NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament games in March.

The Shockers won their first six games in the arena but have now lost two straight, including a 93-76 loss to Oklahoma State last season.

MANEK MOMENTUM

Manek, a 6-foot-9 freshman from Harrah, Oklahoma, had only attempted more than nine shots in one game this season. He had 10 by halftime Saturday, and that was a great thing for the Sooners.

Manek was 6 of 10 from the field and 4 of 8 from the 3-point line in the first half. His 16 points were more than any two Shockers combined.

"Brady had a really good rhythm, so we just kept going to that play," Young said.

BIG PICTURE:

Oklahoma: The Sooners will vault into the rankings, and Young should become even more of a household name.

Wichita State: The Shockers missed their final opportunity for a marquee non-conference victory, one that might hurt them for NCAA Tournament seedings.

UP NEXT

Oklahoma: The Sooners face visiting Northwestern State on Tuesday

Wichita State: The Shockers play visiting Arkansas State on Tuesday.

---
